{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/file-chores-done-by-my-secret-python-bot-c84ea73253c0", "time": 1683017649.17308, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/file-chores-done-by-my-secret-python-bot-c84ea73253c0/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "File chores done by my secret Python bot | by Tiantian Yuan | Towards Data Science", "h1": "File chores done by my secret Python bot", "description": "I have an assistant that handles file chores on my computer. It can finish a chore in 3 minutes that would otherwise take one hour. This python class (file_bot_pdf) is called \u2018bot\u2019 (Figure 1). I\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siri", "anchor_text": "Siri", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K8L6KVGG-7o", "anchor_text": "Python Tutorial: re Module \u2014 How to Write and Match Regular Expressions (Regex).", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://github.com/yuantt83/project_examples/blob/main/file_bots/file_bot_pdf.ipynb", "anchor_text": "Github", "paragraph_index": 10}, {"url": "https://github.com/yuantt83/project_examples/tree/main/file_bots", "anchor_text": "GitHub here", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["I have an assistant that handles file chores on my computer. It can finish a chore in 3 minutes that would otherwise take one hour. This python class (file_bot_pdf) is called \u2018bot\u2019 (Figure 1). I present it here as a pre-Christmas gift to those who may find it useful, useless, cute, boring, or nerdy.", "Chores are must-do tasks that are repetitive and not fun. My recent top 4 file-related chores are: searching for files, deleting files, copying files to folders, and merging pdfs. In a bizarrely isolated 2020, I find myself talking to Siri more. I am annoyed with Siri more than ever: it never finds the files I ask for nor can it delete, copy or merge. So I created my own assistant who could handle files accurately with minimal inputs. It does not interact with voices and it can only do 5 simple things. It is NOT the Siri-kind of an assistant, but I envision a near-future Siri takes over my bot\u2019s job.", "Take the following chore for example.", "I have 30 folders containing 200+ pdf files (Figure 2). Each folder is a data science course that I took. Each course contains subfolders and files of various formats (pdf, png, doc etc), including chapter-based lecture notes (in pdf). Lecture notes for each course follow slightly different naming conventions (see Figure 2, left).", "I would like to combine the lecture notes for each course into a single pdf, so that it is easy to review the course by opening one pdf. I may wish to combine all course notes too, so that I have a giant book of reference (Figure 2, right).", "I want minimal involvement in this boring task. Just like talking Siri, I only need to provide a directory name and a search pattern for the files. The assistant shall take care of the rest on its own.", "Here are 6 lines of python to finish the chore described above using the bot:", "Line 3 is where most of the human brain power is spent. The complexity of regular expressions (regex) required to locate the files varies case by case. The character \u2018r\u2019 before the string means treating regex as raw strings. In the example above, the regex means pdf files with names containing \u2018chapter\u2019, or starting with \u2018ch\u2019, or ending with \u2018_slides\u2019.", "Mastering the art of regex will give you a superpower in programming. For a good youtube tutorial, I recommend \u201cPython Tutorial: re Module \u2014 How to Write and Match Regular Expressions (Regex).\u201d", "The boolean in Line 5 let the user check whether the power of regex is properly honoured. Figure 3 shows what the printout of Line 5 looks like.", "And boom! From typing a few lines of code, checking for errors, to waiting for the 101.62s of merging 129 pdfs, the total task time was 3 minutes and 11 seconds. I didn\u2019t show the example of a final merge of all pdfs (it resulted in a pdf of 3200 pages!). The idea is the same \u2014 simply instantiate another bot with a different filename pattern to capture output files from Line 6 (*_tree_merged.pdf) and it will do the job. This Jupyter notebook on Github has an example of using method .pdf_merge_all, with more detailed descriptions of how to use the module.", "\u201cObject-oriented programming offers a sustainable way to write spaghetti code. It lets you accrete programs as a series of patches.\u201d \u2015 Paul Graham, Hackers & Painters: Big Ideas from the Computer Age", "file_bot_pdf.py is available on GitHub here. I am constantly adding more methods so that the bot can do more types of chores \u2014 the advantage of object-oriented programming (OOP)! You may not have exactly the same chores as I have, so feel free to hack the bot to meet your needs. I hope this post inspires you to write your own python objects to solve problems, or simply, to have some fun with OOP.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Astrophysicist, Data Scientist, Barista. Have a growth mindset and deeply curious about the world. My decisions are driven by data and humanity."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fc84ea73253c0&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffile-chores-done-by-my-secret-python-bot-c84ea73253c0&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Ffile-chores-done-by-my-secret-python-bot-c84ea73253c0&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------